<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,845,1954]" pageId="1" pageNumber="39">
Trichomes are widely used in taxomomic studies in the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Suddee &amp; Paton" authorityYear="2006" box="[955,1082,1734,1760]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Lamiaceae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Cantino, P. D." box="[1099,1264,1734,1760]" pageId="1" pageNumber="39" pagination="323 - 370" refId="ref2414" refString="Cantino, P. D. (1990) The phylogenetics significance of stomata and trichomes in the Labiatae and Verbenaceae. Journal of the Arnold Arboretum 71: 323 - 370." type="journal article" year="1990">Cantino 1990</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gairola, S. &amp; Naidoo, Y. &amp; Bhatt, A. &amp; Nicholas, A." pageId="1" pageNumber="39" pagination="325 - 330" refId="ref2547" refString="Gairola, S., Naidoo, Y., Bhatt, A. &amp; Nicholas, A. (2009) An investigation of the foliar trichomes of Tetradenia riparia (Hochst.) Codd (Lamiaceae): An important medicinal plant of Southern Africa. Flora 204: 325 - 330. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. flora. 2008.04.002" type="journal article" year="2009">
Gairola 
<emphasis box="[1375,1429,1735,1760]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="39">et al</emphasis>
. 2009
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Xiang, C. L. &amp; Dong, Z. H. &amp; Peng, H. &amp; Liu, Z. W." box="[224,428,1773,1799]" pageId="1" pageNumber="39" pagination="434 - 441" refId="ref3471" refString="Xiang, C. L., Dong, Z. H., Peng, H. &amp; Liu, Z. W. (2010) Trichome micromorphology of the East Asiatic genus Chelonopsis (Lamiaceae) and its systematic implications. Flora 205: 434 - 441. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. flora. 2009.12.007" type="journal article" year="2010">
Xiang 
<emphasis box="[302,352,1773,1798]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="39">et al</emphasis>
. 2010
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Hu, G. X. &amp; Balangcod, T. D. &amp; Xiang, C. L." box="[440,612,1773,1799]" pageId="1" pageNumber="39" pagination="867 - 874" refId="ref2765" refString="Hu, G. X., Balangcod, T. D. &amp; Xiang, C. L. (2012) Trichome micromorphology of the Chinese-Himalayan genus Colquhounia (Lamiaceae), with emphasis on taxonomic implications. Biologia, Section Botany 67: 867 - 874. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.2478 / s 11756 - 012 - 0076 - z" type="journal article" year="2012">
Hu 
<emphasis box="[483,533,1773,1798]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="39">et al</emphasis>
. 2012
</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Desfontaines" authorityYear="1815" box="[661,806,1773,1798]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Pogostemon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[661,806,1773,1798]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="39">Pogostemon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, most species have multi-cellular, simple hairs except for two species that have unicellular hairs (
<bibRefCitation author="Bhatti, G. R. &amp; Ingrouille, M." box="[658,956,1812,1838]" pageId="1" pageNumber="39" pagination="77 - 147" refId="ref2327" refString="Bhatti, G. R. &amp; Ingrouille, M. (1997) Systematics of Pogostemon (Labiatae). Bulletin of the Natural History Museum, Botany Series 27: 77 - 147." type="book chapter" year="1997">Bhatti &amp; Ingrouille 1997</bibRefCitation>
). We observed the trichome morphology of leaves of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Doan ex Gang Yao, Y. F. Deng &amp; X. J. Ge" authorityYear="2013" box="[293,418,1851,1876]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Pogostemon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="petelotii">
<emphasis box="[293,418,1851,1876]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="39">P. petelotii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kuntze" authorityYear="1891" baseAuthorityName="Bentham" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[474,615,1851,1876]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Pogostemon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cruciatus">
<emphasis box="[474,615,1851,1876]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="39">P.cruciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
under scanning electron microscopy and light microscopy. The results showed that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Doan ex Gang Yao, Y. F. Deng &amp; X. J. Ge" authorityYear="2013" box="[298,423,1889,1914]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Pogostemon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="petelotii">
<emphasis box="[298,423,1889,1914]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="39">P. petelotii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has unicellular hairs (
<figureCitation box="[681,774,1889,1915]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,245,1931,1952]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,462,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-196@4.[151,1436,462,1915]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Trichome morphology of leaves under scanning electron microscope and light microscope. Pogostemon cruciatus (G. Forrest 25140, IBSC): A. Trichome on the upper surface; C. Trichome on the lower surface; E. 2–3-cellular trichome. P. petelotii (T. Sörensen et al. 6313, KUN): B. Trichome on the upper surface; D. Trichome on lower surface; F. unicellular trichome. Scale bars: E–F = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071563" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071563/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="39">Fig. 3 F</figureCitation>
) more densely covered on the leaf surfaces (
<figureCitation box="[1294,1422,1889,1915]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,245,1931,1952]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,462,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-196@4.[151,1436,462,1915]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Trichome morphology of leaves under scanning electron microscope and light microscope. Pogostemon cruciatus (G. Forrest 25140, IBSC): A. Trichome on the upper surface; C. Trichome on the lower surface; E. 2–3-cellular trichome. P. petelotii (T. Sörensen et al. 6313, KUN): B. Trichome on the upper surface; D. Trichome on lower surface; F. unicellular trichome. Scale bars: E–F = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071563" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071563/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="39">Fig 3 B, D</figureCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kuntze" authorityYear="1891" baseAuthorityName="Bentham" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[200,342,1928,1953]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Pogostemon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cruciatus">
<emphasis box="[200,342,1928,1953]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="39">P.cruciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has 2–3-cellular hairs (
<figureCitation box="[614,709,1928,1954]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,245,1931,1952]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,462,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-196@4.[151,1436,462,1915]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Trichome morphology of leaves under scanning electron microscope and light microscope. Pogostemon cruciatus (G. Forrest 25140, IBSC): A. Trichome on the upper surface; C. Trichome on the lower surface; E. 2–3-cellular trichome. P. petelotii (T. Sörensen et al. 6313, KUN): B. Trichome on the upper surface; D. Trichome on lower surface; F. unicellular trichome. Scale bars: E–F = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071563" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071563/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="39">Fig. 3 E</figureCitation>
) more sparsely covered on the leaf surfaces (
<figureCitation box="[1239,1375,1928,1954]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,245,1931,1952]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,462,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-196@4.[151,1436,462,1915]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Trichome morphology of leaves under scanning electron microscope and light microscope. Pogostemon cruciatus (G. Forrest 25140, IBSC): A. Trichome on the upper surface; C. Trichome on the lower surface; E. 2–3-cellular trichome. P. petelotii (T. Sörensen et al. 6313, KUN): B. Trichome on the upper surface; D. Trichome on lower surface; F. unicellular trichome. Scale bars: E–F = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071563" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071563/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="39">Fig. 3 A, C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
